---

<SiteLayout
  title={pageTitle}
  siteTitle={siteTitle}
  description="An Astro + TypeScript tutor site for SRJC ANAT 1, modeled after a structured class resource page with topic navigation and grouped handouts."
>
  <main class="bg-white px-4 py-6 md:px-10 md:py-8">
    <div class="mb-1.5 text-[0.9rem] text-neutral-500">{siteTitle}</div>
    <h1 class="mb-5 text-[2rem] font-normal leading-tight text-neutral-800">
      {pageHeading}
    </h1>
    <details class="mt-10 border border-neutral-300 bg-white" open={false}>
      <summary class="cursor-pointer list-none px-4 py-4 md:px-8">
        <div class="flex items-center justify-between gap-4">
          <div>
            <h2 class="text-[1.2rem] font-semibold text-neutral-800">
              Must-Know Digestive Histology
            </h2>
            <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-neutral-600">
              Expand to review the key histology images before using the
              flowchart.
            </p>
          </div>

          <span
            class="shrink-0 rounded border border-neutral-300 bg-neutral-50 px-3 py-1 text-sm text-neutral-700 transition details-open:rotate-180"
          >
            SHOW
          </span>
        </div>
      </summary>

      <div class="border-t border-neutral-300 px-4 py-6 md:px-8">
        <div class="max-w-5xl">
          <p class="mb-4 text-neutral-600">
            Before getting deeper into digestive system studying, make sure you
            can recognize these high-yield histology images. These are some of
            the most important tissues and structures to know before using the
            flowchart below.
          </p>

          <div class="space-y-6">
            <figure class="border border-neutral-300 bg-neutral-50 p-3">
              <img
                src="/images/digestive/esophagus_sset.png"
                alt="Esophagus histology"
                class="mb-3 h-auto w-full border border-neutral-200 bg-white"
              />
              <figcaption class="text-sm text-neutral-700">
                <strong class="block text-neutral-800">Esophagus</strong>
                Stratified squamous epithelium; look for protection against abrasion.
              </figcaption>
            </figure>

            <figure class="border border-neutral-300 bg-neutral-50 p-3">
              <img
                src="/images/digestive/villi.png"
                alt="Small intestine villi"
                class="mb-3 h-auto w-full border border-neutral-200 bg-white"
              />
              <figcaption class="text-sm text-neutral-700">
                <strong class="block text-neutral-800">
                  Villi of the small intestine (all 3 parts)
                </strong>
                Villi: finger-like projections that extend into the lumen.
              </figcaption>
            </figure>

            <figure class="border border-neutral-300 bg-neutral-50 p-3">
              <img
                src="/images/digestive/brunners.png"
                alt="Brunner's glands histology"
                class="mb-3 h-auto w-full border border-neutral-200 bg-white"
              />
              <figcaption class="text-sm text-neutral-700">
                <strong class="block text-neutral-800">
                  Brunner's glands in the duodenum
                </strong>
                Villi plus submucosal Brunner glands are the key giveaway.
              </figcaption>
            </figure>

            <figure class="border border-neutral-300 bg-neutral-50 p-3">
              <img
                src="/images/digestive/peyers.jpg"
                alt="Peyer's patches histology"
                class="mb-3 h-auto w-full border border-neutral-200 bg-white"
              />
              <figcaption class="text-sm text-neutral-700">
                <strong class="block text-neutral-800">
                  Peyer's patches in the ileum
                </strong>
                Look for Peyer's patches and many goblet cells.
              </figcaption>
            </figure>

            <figure class="border border-neutral-300 bg-neutral-50 p-3">
              <img
                src="/images/digestive/gastric_pits.png"
                alt="Stomach histology"
                class="mb-3 h-auto w-full border border-neutral-200 bg-white"
              />
              <figcaption class="text-sm text-neutral-700">
                <strong class="block text-neutral-800">Stomach</strong>
                Gastric pits of the stomach.
              </figcaption>
            </figure>

            <figure class="border border-neutral-300 bg-neutral-50 p-3">
              <img
                src="/images/digestive/stomach_cells_fundus.png"
                alt="Fundic stomach histology"
                class="mb-3 h-auto w-full border border-neutral-200 bg-white"
              />
              <figcaption class="text-sm text-neutral-700">
                <strong class="block text-neutral-800">Stomach (Fundus)</strong>
                Parietal cells (pink fried eggs) and Chief cells (yellow waypoint)
              </figcaption>
            </figure>

            <figure class="border border-neutral-300 bg-neutral-50 p-3">
              <img
                src="/images/digestive/large_intestine.png"
                alt="Large intestine histology"
                class="mb-3 h-auto w-full border border-neutral-200 bg-white"
              />
              <figcaption class="text-sm text-neutral-700">
                <strong class="block text-neutral-800">Large Intestine</strong>
                NO VILLI; has goblet cells and intestinal glands
              </figcaption>
            </figure>

            <figure class="border border-neutral-300 bg-neutral-50 p-3">
              <img
                src="/images/digestive/liver_lobule.jpg"
                alt="Liver histology"
                class="mb-3 h-auto w-full border border-neutral-200 bg-white"
              />
              <figcaption class="text-sm text-neutral-700">
                <strong class="block text-neutral-800">Liver</strong>
                Hepatic lobule pattern, central veins, and portal triads.
              </figcaption>
            </figure>

            <figure class="border border-neutral-300 bg-neutral-50 p-3">
              <img
                src="/images/digestive/pancreatic_islets.png"
                alt="Pancreas histology"
                class="mb-3 h-auto w-full border border-neutral-200 bg-white"
              />
              <figcaption class="text-sm text-neutral-700">
                <strong class="block text-neutral-800">Pancreas</strong>
                Darker exocrine tissue with lighter-staining pancreatic islets.
              </figcaption>
            </figure>

            <figure class="border border-neutral-300 bg-neutral-50 p-3">
              <img
                src="/images/digestive/salivary_glands.png"
                alt="Salivary gland histology"
                class="mb-3 h-auto w-full border border-neutral-200 bg-white"
              />
              <figcaption class="text-sm text-neutral-700">
                <strong class="block text-neutral-800">Salivary Gland</strong>
                NO ISLETS, NO LOBULES. Serous and mucous cells.
              </figcaption>
            </figure>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <section class="mt-8 border border-neutral-300 bg-white px-4 py-6 md:px-8">
      <div class="max-w-5xl">
        <h2 class="mb-2 text-[1.2rem] font-semibold text-neutral-800">
          Digestive Histology Flowchart
        </h2>

        <p class="mb-4 text-neutral-600">
          After reviewing the Must-Know Digestive Histology above, use this
          flowchart to compare the major digestive organs and tissues by their
          most recognizable features.
        </p>

        <div
          class="mb-4 border border-emerald-200 bg-emerald-50 px-4 py-3 text-sm text-emerald-900"
        >
          <strong class="font-semibold">How to use it:</strong> start at the top and
          work through the distinguishing features step by step. Try identifying the
          tissue on your own before checking the flowchart.
        </div>

        <div class="mb-4 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
          <a
            href="/downloads/dig_sys_histo_flow_chart.pdf"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noreferrer"
            class="inline-block rounded border border-neutral-300 bg-neutral-50 px-4 py-2 text-blue-700 no-underline hover:bg-neutral-100 hover:underline"
          >
            View PDF
          </a>

          <a
            href="/downloads/dig_sys_histo_flow_chart.pdf"
            download
            class="inline-block rounded border border-neutral-300 bg-neutral-50 px-4 py-2 text-blue-700 no-underline hover:bg-neutral-100 hover:underline"
          >
            Download PDF
          </a>
        </div>

        <div class="overflow-hidden border border-neutral-300 bg-neutral-50">
          <iframe
            src="/downloads/dig_sys_histo_flow_chart.pdf"
            title="Digestive histology flowchart PDF"
            class="h-175 w-full bg-white"></iframe>
        </div>

        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-neutral-500">
          If the PDF preview does not load on your device, use the buttons above
          to open or download it directly.
        </p>

        <div
          class="mt-6 border border-blue-200 bg-blue-50 px-4 py-3 text-sm text-blue-900"
        >
          <strong class="font-semibold">Study tip:</strong> PRINT THIS OUT AND BRING TO LAB WITH YOU. Use the images above or slides in lab and
          this flowchart together. Go back and forth between them until you can explain
          why each tissue belongs where it does.
        </div>
                <div
          class="mt-6 border border-blue-200 bg-blue-50 px-4 py-3 text-sm text-blue-900"
        >
          <strong class="font-semibold">Study tip:</strong> Find a partner in lab and test each other on random digestive system slides to try and identify them.
        </div>

        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-neutral-500">
          Original flowchart source:
          <a
            href="https://sites.google.com/view/srjcanatomy1/links-and-handouts/digestive-system"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noreferrer"
            class="text-blue-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-blue-800"
          >
            "Digestive Histology Flow Chart" from Danielle King's SRJC Anatomy 1
            Digestive System page
          </a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
    {
      groups.map((group) => (
        <section
          class="mt-8"
          aria-labelledby={group.title
            .toLowerCase()
            .replace(/[^a-z0-9]+/g, "-")}
        >
          <h2
            id={group.title.toLowerCase().replace(/[^a-z0-9]+/g, "-")}
            class="mb-2 text-[1.2rem] font-semibold text-neutral-800"
          >
            {group.title}
          </h2>
          {group.description && (
            <p class="mb-3.5 text-base text-neutral-500">{group.description}</p>
          )}
          <ul class="m-0 list-disc pl-[1.35rem]">
            {group.links.map((link) => (
              <li class="my-2">
                <a
                  href={link.url}
                  target={link.url.endsWith(".apkg") ? undefined : "_blank"}
                  rel={link.url.endsWith(".apkg") ? undefined : "noreferrer"}
                  download={link.url.endsWith(".apkg") ? true : undefined}
                  class="text-blue-700 underline-offset-2 hover:underline"
                >
                  {link.title}
                </a>
                {link.note && (
                  <div class="mt-0.5 text-[0.94rem] text-neutral-500">
                    {link.note}
                  </div>
                )}
              </li>
            ))}
          </ul>
        </section>
      ))
    }
  </main>
</SiteLayout>
